weapon.name: VGO
weapon.description: The VGO began life as an airplane-mounted machine gun. But it was soon adopted for land use. A high rate of fire made it a favorite among Allied commando units.

weapon.name: Solveig's Knife
weapon.description: A hunting knife from the Northern part of Europe. Useful for skinning and gutting all sorts of fish and game. A classic utility blade that can also be used for self-defence.

weapon.name: Broken Bottle
weapon.description: Improvised weapons were often a necessity during wartime. Bottles tended to be in abundance both in urban and rural situations, whether they were discovered or property of the soldiers.

weapon.name: EGW Survival Knife
weapon.description: The EGW survival knife was never officially issued by the US Army, though soldiers often bought one for themselves. They were very versatile with a serrated back edge but were also prone to rust.

weapon.name: Combat Knife
weapon.description: A combat and utility knife designed as much as a tool as it is a weapon.

weapon.name: Barbed Baseball Bat
weapon.description: Not a conventional weapon on the battlefield, but a useful one nonetheless.

weapon.name: Arditi Dagger
weapon.description: The Arditi were an elite unit of Italian shock troops during World War I. Disbanding after the war, they were notorious for employing daggers as their primary weapon.

weapon.name: Sticky Dynamite
weapon.description: Sticky bundle of dynamite that can be placed and detonated on demand. Effective against structures, vehicles and infantry.

weapon.name: Bandages
weapon.description: Single-use field dressings that heal a single soldier on the move. Any damage will cancel the heal.

weapon.name: AT Mine
weapon.description: Anti-Tank Mines will explode and cause significant damage when traversed by enemy vehicles.

weapon.name: AP Mine
weapon.description: The Schrapnellmine or ''Bouncing Betty'' is a tripwire anti-personnel mine. When triggered, it bounces up and deploys a lethal spray of shrapnel that can only be avoided by quickly going prone.

weapon.name: Sticky Grenade
weapon.description: A lighter, but sticky anti tank grenade. Effective against armored vehicles.

weapon.name: Throwing Blade
weapon.description: A sharp and well balanced blade to silently take down an enemy from a distance.

weapon.name: Medical Syringe
weapon.description: An adrenaline injection that can be used to revive downed allies.

weapon.name: Shaped Charge
weapon.description: A magnetic explosive charge that can be attached to vehicles. Detonated by time fuze.

weapon.name: Kunai
weapon.description: Most likely derived from a masonry or gardening tool and transformed into a formidable and silent throwing weapon.

weapon.name: Doppel-Schuss
weapon.description: Adopted by German naval crews as they rose to prominence early in the war. Used to signal and illuminate where no other lights were available, in the middle of the sea.

weapon.name: Type 99 Mine
weapon.description: A light, thrown, anti-tank mine that sticks only to vehicles and explodes on a timer between 5-10 seconds. Two of these light mines are carried at once.

weapon.name: Firecrackers
weapon.description: Used to similate the sounds of gunfire to confuse the enemy and their information systems.

weapon.name: RMN50 Rifle Frag
weapon.description: More hand mortar then grenade launcher, the RMN50 fires standard 50mm mortar shells from a converted Mosin-Nagant that will explode after a timer, even in midair.

weapon.name: Demolition Grenade
weapon.description: The No.75 Hawkins grenade works as a low power anti-tank mine, and can be thrown a longer distance than a tranditional heavy anti-tank mine.

weapon.name: Pistol Flamethrower
weapon.description: A hand held, disposable, flamethrower firing a short burst of flame that can devastate individual infantry targets.

weapon.name: Repetierpistole M1912
weapon.description: The M1912 was a rugged and dependable pistol with an integral magazine. First used in World War I, the German Army ordered 60,000 pistols when Germany annexed Austria in 1938.

weapon.name: Type 94
weapon.description: Manufactured in Japan since before the war, some viewed this pistol as being unnecessarily complex in its design while others admired that it was compact and lightweight.

weapon.name: Welrod
weapon.description: The British developed the Welrod pistol to be as quiet as possible. It was bolt-operated and magazine fed. At only 73 dBA, it was about as loud as a present-day car.

weapon.name: PPK
weapon.description: Designed in 1929, the PPK is the short version of the PP.  While the newer P38 was the standard sidearm of German military during World War II the PPK was adopted in small numbers throughout the war.

weapon.name: PPKS
weapon.description: Designed in 1929, the PPK is the short version of the PP.  While the newer P38 was the standard sidearm of German military during World War II the PPK was adopted in small numbers throughout the war.
